y fiction of Leslie Marmon Silko and Kim Stanley Robinson. Each of these cultural and literary texts provides a window into the possible constitution of a (distributed) environmental politics that does not yet exist and operates as a resource for envisioning environmental actors we cannot necessarily study empirically, because they are still only a prospect, or potential, of our imagination.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAgent (Philosophy)xPolitical aspects. 0aEnvironmental policy. 0aEnvironmentalismxPolitical aspects. 4aEnvironmental Studies : Environmental Politics. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Theory. 4aSociology : Social Movements. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2021z978311149169140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848439640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438484396423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438484396/original  a978-3-11-149169-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles